1. Token count (9,094) is below the exercise sheet's expected range of 15,000-16,000.
   This likely means the source text file (txt/01telemachus.txt) is an abridged or
   differently edited version, or the expected range was calibrated against a different
   edition. Verify the source text is complete.

2. The Zipf's Law section of the exercise asks for an R-squared value from a log-log
   linear regression (expected > 0.90), but zipf_plot() only overlays an ideal C/r line
   without computing or printing R-squared. Add a scipy.stats.linregress or
   numpy.polyfit on log(rank) vs. log(freq) and print the R-squared.

3. The TTR (0.2731) falls slightly below the exercise sheet's expected range of
   0.28-0.35. This is likely a consequence of the lower-than-expected token count
   (issue 1). If the source text is confirmed complete, the expected range in the
   exercise sheet may need adjustment.

4. The hapax ratio (0.6552) is above the exercise sheet's expected range of 0.45-0.55.
   This could indicate a genuine property of the text or could be inflated by a
   shorter-than-expected text (shorter texts tend to have higher hapax ratios). Revisit
   after resolving issue 1.

5. The Emma comparison uses a character-count-based excerpt (emma_text[:len(telemachus)])
   which may truncate mid-sentence or mid-word. Consider truncating at a sentence
   boundary for a cleaner comparison.

6. "said" and "asked" are dialogue tags that function almost like stopwords in a
   fiction corpus. Consider noting this in the analysis or optionally filtering them
   to see what thematic vocabulary sits beneath.
